MPM03 - Toolbox with RMarkdown

By Eliane Albisser, Nicolasa Ana Caduff, Dominik Gabler, Michael Wechsler

GENERAL

Introduction:

This toolbox will focus on unsupervised learning methods. Unsupervised learning is a set of statistical tools intended for the setting in which we have only a set of features measured on n observations.

In unsupervised learning, we are not interested in prediction, because we do not have an associated response variable Y. Rather, the goal is to discover interesting things about the measurements and the features. Therefore, unsupervised learning wants to visualize data in an informative way or discover subgroups among variables or among the observations.

Unsupervised learning is often performed as part of an exploratory data analysis. Often, it can be hard to assess the results obtained from unsupervised learning methods. Different from supervised methods (response variable), unsupervised learning has no way to check the work because we don’t know the true answer - the problem is unsupervised.

In this Toolbox, the following methods are covered:

  • K-means
  • Hierarchical Clustering (HC)
  • Principal Component Analysis (PCA)
  • T-distributed Stochastic Neighbor Embedding (tSNE)
  • Self-organizing Maps (SOM)

Dataset

The default database for the toolbox is a reduced version of the FIFA 19 player dataset. It includes detailed attributes for every registered player in the FIFA 19 video game. The data set contains 40 different metrics (e.g. Salary per week, value, Dribbling, BallControl) and categorical (e.g. Position) attributes (features) for n=6699 different players (observations).

As described below, the dataset can easily be changed thanks to the usage of knitr-parameters and if-clauses.

Toolbox structure and handling

The Toolbox has a very dynamic structure. In the interactive user interface based on Shiny (start via: Knit/Knit with Parameters) the user can select another data set, determine data variables (first numerical and second numerical variable) for the data analyses in the toolbox and define which of the above mentioned unsupervised machine learning methods he wants to execute (checkboxes).

Of course it is not already complete, but there can easily be added some more datatypes for example. Therefore, only few changes in code are necessary.

We will highly recommend to create html-output and not pdf or word. Only if html-output is used, you can benefit from the good structure by using css and some other fancy stuff for better understanding.

Have fun!

PLOTS

Aim:

  • Exploration of the data
  • Better understand the data and to see what kind of relationship there is between the predictor and the response variable

Standard Plot

Description:

  • Plotting the response variable Dribbling (defined as “first_variable” above) against BallControl (defined as “second_variable” above)
  • Visualization of the positions with categorical variable
  • Verification of the assumption that good Dribbling skills require a good ball control
  • Quantify the visual impressions with the correlation coefficient
ggplot(data, mapping = aes(y = data_second_variable, x = data_first_variable, color=data_categorical_variable)) +
  geom_point() +
  ggtitle("Standard Plot of two defined exploration variables") +
  theme(plot.title=element_text(size = 10, face="bold")) +
  labs(x=first_variable, y=second_variable, color=categorical_variable)

cor(data_second_variable, data_first_variable)
[1] 0.94

Interpretation:

  • As expected, there’s a clear connection between dribbling skills and ball control -> plausibility check of data
  • The positive correlation between dribbling skills and ball control can be quantified with the correlation coefficient. The correlation coefficient is 0.9. Thus, there is a strong positive linear correlation between dribbling skills and ball control.
  • The dot color visualizes the position of the players. It is recognisable that
    • Nearly all goalkeepers have low dribbling skills and low ball control
    • Defenders tend to have low to medium dribbling skills and ball control
    • Midfield seems to be the most popular position. They have medium to high dribbling skills and ball control
    • Strikers have medium to high dribbling skills and ball control

Standard Plot with regression line

Description:

  • In the following plot, a regression line will be added to visualize the linear relationship between the exploration variables dribbling skills and ball control.
  • To analyze (visualize and calculate key figures) the linear relationship of the exploration variables is important if we want to fit regression model afterwards.
ggplot(data, mapping = aes(y = data_second_variable, x = data_first_variable, color=data_categorical_variable)) +
  geom_point() +
  ggtitle("Plot with regression line of two defined exploration variables") +
  theme(plot.title=element_text(size = 10, face="bold")) +
  labs(x=first_variable, y=second_variable, color=categorical_variable) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")

Interpretation:

  • Unsurprisingly, the regression line shows for all positions a strong positive relationship between dribbling skills and ball control.
  • According to the regression line, the linear relationship between dribbling skills and ball control is highest among strikers (highest slope of the line), followed by midfielders and defenders.

Standard Plot with smoother

Description:

  • The relationship of two predictors could also be non-linear.
  • To verify the linearity assumption for the predictors we are adding a smoother rather than a regression line to the graph.
ggplot(data, mapping = aes(y = data_second_variable, x = data_first_variable, color=data_categorical_variable)) +

  • The graph contains a lot of information and is therefore a little bit overloaded. The following approach “Paneling” may help to get a better overview.

Paneling

Description:

  • Sometimes, the graphs are quite full of information and therefore no longer easy to interpret.
  • A different approach to visualise the effect of the connection between Dribbling skills and BallControl for each payer position is to use “paneling”.
  • Panelling means that the observation of each payer position will be plotted in a different panel.
ggplot(data = data,mapping = aes(y = data_second_variable,x = data_first_variable)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(data_categorical_variable) +
  labs(x=first_variable, y=second_variable)

Interpretation:

  • Panels show the same information like the graphs before.
  • Advantage is, that we can see the relationship between Dribbling skills and BallControl for each player position in a separate panel.
  • As mentioned above, there is a clear positive relationship between Dribbling skills and BallControl for all positions.

Boxplot

Description:

  • To see the differences in dribbling skills between the four player positions, we create a boxplot.
  • Boxplots summarize data and help to outline differences in the data among a categorical variable (e.g. position).
ggplot(data, mapping = aes(y = data_first_variable, x = fct_reorder(data_categorical_variable, data_first_variable, .fun = median, .desc = FALSE))) +
  ggtitle(paste("Boxplot:", first_variable, "per", categorical_variable)) +
  labs(x="", y=first_variable) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill = fct_reorder(data_categorical_variable, data_first_variable))) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = brewer.pal(n_distinct(data_categorical_variable), "Dark2"),
                    guide = guide_legend(title = categorical_variable)) +
  theme_bw(base_size = 12) +
  theme(plot.title=element_text(size = 10, face="bold"))

Interpretation:

  • It is clearly visible that the median of dribbling skills is lowest among the goalkeepers, followed by the defenders.
  • The median of the dribbling skills at midfielder and strikers are about the same, with a small advantage for strikers.
  • It is noticeable that the distribution of skills per position group varies strongly.
  • Goalkeepers have the smallest distribution (inter-quartile-range, all low dribbling skills), while defenders have a very high spread of dribbling skills.
  • Midfielders and strikers have the lower distribution compared to the defenders. Nevertheless, midfielders have a lot of outliers.

K-MEANS CLUSTERING

K-means clustering is a simple and elegant approach for partitioning a data set into K distinct, non-overlapping clusters. To perform K-means clustering, we must first specify the desired number of clusters K and then the K-means algorithm will assign each observation to exactly one of the clusters.

Description:

  • Unsupervised
  • Parametric (Pre-specification of K number necessary)

Functionality:

  • Groups data based on their similarity, the resulting clusters have similar properties
  • Push the data into K pre-determined categories
    • Choose a number K of cluster centers
    • Place the centers randomly in the data space (initial cluster assignment)
    • Iteratively move the centers to minimize the total within cluster variance (data-center distance)

Aim:

  • First exploration of multidimensional data (assumption about K needed).

Fields of application:

  • Market segmentation (e.g. identify some clusters of your customers in your company)
  • Medical examination (e.g. tumour detection)
  • Fraud detection

Further information:

  • Difference between HC and k-means
    • Compared to HC, k-means need a specified number of K clusters
    • k-means forces the data into K pre-determined categories

Plotting k-means

What we do? (Code)

We create a simple two dimensional kmeans-plot with 2, 3 or 5 centroids using our definied two variables from the very beginning (Dribbling & BallControl).

Note: kmeans(x, centers, nstart), x = numeric matrix of data, centers = number of initial centers (=centroids), nstart = number of random sets

km_choice <- c(2, 3, 5)
for (i in km_choice){
  km.out <- kmeans(selection_exploration_data,i,nstart =50)
  plot(selection_exploration_data,
       col = (km.out$cluster+1),
       main = paste("k-means clustering with", i, "centroids"),
       cex.main = 0.8,
       xlab = first_variable,
       ylab = second_variable,
       pch = 20, cex = 2)
}

What we get? (Interpretation)

  • Plot k-means (centroids: 3)
    • Plot shows three clearly divisible groups.
    • Results can be easily plotted due to the case, that we have two-dimensional data.
    • If we would have more than two variables, we could instead perform PCA and plot the first two principal components score vectors.
  • Model-Output: km.out (centroids: 3)
    • Output shows for each observation (e.g. Playername), to which group the observation was allocated.
    • In one example, the method made a clustering with 3 clusters of sizes 132, 39, 29 (=200 observations)
    • E.g. Messi (1), Ronaldo (2) and Neymar (3) are allocated in one group (e.g. 3rd group), De Gea in another group (e.g. 1st Group).
  • km.out$withinss (centroids: 3)
    • The individual within-cluster sum-of-squares (one component per cluster)
    • Shows how dissimilar are the members of a group are. The greater is the sum, the greater is the dissimilarity within a group.
    • The first cluster has a sum-of-squares of 5755, the second 3593 and the third 3273. Therefore, the dissimilarity in the first Group is the biggest.
  • km.out$tot.withins (centroids: 3):
    • Total within-cluster sum of squares, which we seek to minimize by performing K-means clustering
    • Total within-cluster sum of squares is 12620. This is a measure of the quality of the model. The lower the measure, the better the model.

In the next step, we will check how the different key-figures behave with a different number of centroids

Plotting k-means numbers

What we do? (Code)

We use a function to check multiple pre-determined values of K and choose the right one (reduce km.out$tot.withins)

wss <- 0
for (i in 1:10){
  km.out <- kmeans(exploration_data,i,nstart =50)
  wss[i] <- km.out$tot.withinss
}

plot(1:10,
     wss,
     type="b",
     xlab="Number of Clusters",
     ylab="Total within-cluster sum of squares")

What we get? (Interpretation)

  • The plot shows, how the Total within-cluster sum of squares can be reduced by increasing the Number of Clusters.
  • If an additional group is added, total sum squares can only decrease. The question is only how many groups make sense.
  • The biggest opimatization step is visible if we increase from 1 to 2 classes. The decrease of Total within-cluster sum of squares decreases the more classes we add.
  • From the increase to 6 or 7 classes, the optimization of the model becomes only minor.

HIERARCHICAL CLUSTERING (HC) & HEAT MAPS

One potential disadvantage of K-means clustering is that it requires to pre-specify the number of clusters (K). Hierarchical clustering is an alternative approach which does not require that we commit to a particular choice of K. The method has an added advantage over K-means clustering in that it results in an attractive tree-based representation of the observations, called a dendrogram.

Description:

  • Unsupervised
  • Non-parametric
  • Linkage methods: “ward.D”, “ward.D2”, “single”, “complete”, “average”, “mcquitty”, “median”,“centroid”
  • Distance methods: “euclidean”, “maximum”, “manhattan”, “canberra”,“binary”, “minkowski”

Functionality:

  • Groups data based on their similarity, the resulting clusters have similar properties
    • Bottom-up agglomerative clustering
    • Can use different metric (Euclidean-, Pearson distance)
    • Generates dendrograms that highlight similar patterns in the data set
    • Often combined to heatmaps graphical representation

Aim:

  • First exploration of multidimensional data (no assumptions needed)

Fields of application:

  • Market segmentation
  • Medical examination (e.g. tumour detection)

Further information:

  • Difference between HC and k-means
    • Compared to k-means, HC doesn’t need to specify k-number of clusters
    • k-means forces the data into K pre-determined categories
  • Difference between HC and PCA
    • Compared to PCA, HC makes homogeneous subgroups of data that have similarities
    • PCA projects multi-dimensional data on a low-dimensional space that best summarizes data variance

Hierarchical Clustering (HC) with R-Standard

What we do? (Code)

We create a dendrogram by using the R-Standard libraries. But we need to do this with scaled data. Then we use the following methods:

  • Linkage method: all possibilities
  • Distance method: euclidean
hc_linkage_methods <- c("ward.D", "ward.D2", "single", "complete", "average", "mcquitty", "median","centroid")

for (i in hc_linkage_methods){
  hc_linkage <- hclust(dist(t_scaled_data, method = "euclidean"),method= i)
  plot(hc_linkage,
       main=paste("Distance method: euclidean,", "Linkage method:", i),
       cex.main=0.8,
       xlab="",
       sub="",
       hang = -1, cex = 0.6)
}

What we get? (Interpretation)

  • Due to the loop, we get different Dendrograms
    • Leaf: Each leaf of the dendrogram represents one of the predictors in the dataset
    • Height: As we move up the tree, some leaves begin to fuse into branches. These correspond to predicotrs/observations that are similar to each other. The earlier (lower in the tree) fusions occur, the more similar the groups of observations are to each other. Nevertheless, the choice of where to cut the dendrogram is not always clear.
  • We can see, that GK-predictors are quite similar to each other, since they fuse at the lowest point on the dendrogram. The same statement we can make for predictors Interceptions, Sliding Tackle and Standing Tackle. Moreover, we see that overall score, value and salary have a high correlation. This means, that the best players have the highest market value und earn the highest amount of money (which make sense of course).
  • On the other hand, we can say that the GK-predictors are quite different from all other predictors.

For the players on the left-hand side we see high values for different finishing skills like Volley, Finishing, Penalties and ShootPower.

Hierarchical Clustering (HC) with Factoextra

What we do? (Code)

We use the Factoextra Package, which offers a more complete library, is simpler to use and contains all methods for distance & linkage. In addition we can create a dissimilarity matrix.

  • Linkage methods: “single”, “complete”, “average”, “centroid”, “ward.D”, “ward.D2”
  • Distance methods (additional): “pearson”, “spearman”, “kendall”

In this case we create first a correlation matrix and then a new cluster dendrogram:

  • Linkage method: complete
  • Distance method: all possibilities
hc_distance_methods <- c("euclidean", "maximum", "manhattan", "canberra","binary", "minkowski", "pearson", "spearman", "kendall")

for (i in hc_distance_methods){
  res.dist <- get_dist(t_scaled_data, method = i)
  plot(fviz_dist(res.dist, lab_size = 6))
  hc_distance <- hclust(res.dist, method = "complete")
  plot(hc_distance,
       main=paste("Distance method: ", i, ", Linkage method: complete"),
       cex.main=0.8,
       xlab="",
       sub="",
       hang = -1, cex = 0.6,)
}

What we get? (Interpretation)

  • Due to the loop, we get different Dendrograms and correlation matrices (with difference distance methods)

  • The results for the Dendrograms are similar like in the Dendrograms above: GK-observations are quite similar to each other and are a good separator for splitting the predictors into groups. The same statement we can make for the defending-predictors like Interceptions, Sliding Tackle and Standing Tackle and for the attacking-predictors like Volley, ShootPower, Penalties and Finishing.

  • Thanks to the Factoextra Package, we can also create nice correlation matrices. The matrices help to visualize in a convenient way, how the different features relate to each other.

  • The presumptions we have from the Dendrograms can be displayed very clearly: very strong correlation in GK-skills, strong correlation in Defender-Skills (Interceptions, Sliding Tackle and Standing Tackle) and for the attacking-features like Volley, ShootPower, Penalties and Finishing.

  • What is also visible is the high correlation between ball control, dribbling, skill moves and agility and negative correlations between GK skills and completion skills (shot power, volleys, etc.).

  • Overall, we can say that the main findings from the different distance methods (type of metric, which is responsible to build homogeneous subgroups, e.g. Euclidean, manhattan, minkowski) are similar.

PRINCIPAL COMPONENT ANALYSIS (PCA)

When faced with a large set of correlated variables, principal components allow us to summarize this set with a smaller number of representative variables that collectively explain most of the variability in the original set.

Description:

  • Unsupervised
  • Non-Parametric
  • Linear

Functionality:

  • Reduces the dimensionality of a dataset and leads to a more understandable representation (Data organization method for grouping variables with similar behaviour)
  • Push the data into K pre-determined categories
    • Find new axes (principal components) that represent the data space in a reduced set of dimensions (capture the most important information in the data)
    • Capture the maximal variance of the data
    • Highlight the global patterns in the data set

Aim:

  • First exploration of multidimensional data (no assumptions needed)

Fields of application:

  • Market segmentation
  • Medical examination (e.g. tumour detection)

Further information:

  • Difference between PCA and HC
    • Compared to HC, PCA projects multi-dimensional data on a low-dimensional space that best summarizes data variance
    • HC makes homogeneous subgroups of data that have similarities based on a distance metric

PCA Starplots

What we do? (Code)

We use a sample of 20 rows and reduce the number of dimensions to 6, so that we can have a look at some starplots.

set.seed(3)

N <- nrow(data_only_numerical)

stars(data_only_numerical[id.sample_data,floor(runif(6,1,20))],
      main = "PCA Starplots sample",
      key.loc = c(13,2),
      cex = 0.6,
      cex.main = 0.8)

What we get? (Interpretation)

  • We get starplots for 20 randomly selected players. The starplots visualize for example the predictors Age, Acceleration, GKPositioneing and Value of the players.
  • For player number 1126 we see high Age, Acceleration, Overall Score and Value, but low GKPositioning Skills.

T-DISTRIBUTED STOCHASTIC NEIGHBOR EMBEDDING (tSNE)

t-Distributed Stochastic Neighbor Embedding (tSNE) is a non-linear technique for dimensionality reduction that is particularly well suited for the visualization of high-dimensional datasets.

Description:

  • Unsupervised
  • Non-Parametric
  • Non-Linear

Functionality:

  • Embeds high-dimensional data in a low-dimensional space to visualize (Data organization method for grouping variables with similar behaviour)
  • tSNE minimizes the difference between the similarity of points in high & in low-dimensional space (according to a conditional probability ruled by a probability distribution)
  • Minimize distributions divergence (Kullback-Leibler divergence, relative entropy) between
    • a similarity distribution of multi-dimensional input objects and
    • a similarity distribution of the corresponding low-dimensional points
    • using a gradient descent

Aim:

  • Exploration & visualization of data, well-suited for high-dimensional data

Fields of application:

  • Market segmentation
  • Medical examination (e.g. tumour detection)
  • –> sometimes tSNE can better separate groups than PCA and HC, especially in higher dimensions

Further information:

  • Difference between tSNE (2008) and PCA (1933)
    • Compared to PCA, tSNE transforms the data via a non-linear operation based on Gaussian / t-distributions
    • PCA projects multi-dimensional data on a low-dimensional space (linear mapping of the data to a low-dimensional space such that variance is maximized)
    • tSNE should be more effective than PCA, capturing more information from the high-dimensional space

What we do? (Code)

We try to get better results by changing the perplexity. The perplexity measures the numbers of close neighbors of each point. A higher perplexity means a data point will consider more points as its close neighbors.

perplexity_choice <- c(2, 5, 10, 20, 30, 50)

for (i in perplexity_choice){

                dims = 2,
                perplexity=i,
                verbose=TRUE,
                max_iter = 500)

}

LESSON 04 / 11.10.2019

SELF-ORGANIZING MAPS (SOM)

The method of Self-Organizing Maps (SOM) is a “machine learning” approach that is commonly used for clustering data sets in which the membership of the training data vectors in some prespecified number of groups G is not known. Self-organizing maps differ from other artificial neural networks as they apply competitive learning (tune neurons location iteratively based on the input and make them compete between each other). Trained SOMs classify inputs by finding the node with the closest distance to the input.

Description:

  • Unsupervised
  • Parametric
  • Non-Linear
  • Type of artificial neural network
  • Somewhat similar to K-means (SOMs with a small number of nodes behave similar to K-means)
  • Somewhat similar to PCA (can be considered a nonlinear generalization of PCA)

Functionality:

  • Reduces the dimensionality of a dataset (similar to PCA and tSNE)
  • Like most artificial neural networks, SOMs operate in two modes: training and mapping
  • Trains a neural network such that parts of it become specifically responsive to certain input patterns
  • Produces a low-dimensional, discrete representation (=map) of the input space of the training samples
  • Mapping from a higher-dimensional input space to a lower-dimensional map space
    • Uses competitive learning (unlike other artificial neural networks, that use error correction learning like backpropagation & gradient descent)
    • Trained SOMs classify inputs by finding the node with the closest distance (smallest metric) to the input

Aim:

  • SOMs are useful for visualization by creating low-dimensional views of high-dimensional data.

Fields of application:

  • Market segmentation
  • Medical examination (e.g. tumour detection)
  • –> SOMs might perform better than other methods in certain situations (e.g. high dimensions)

Further information:

  • Difference between SOM and k-means
    • Neurons ~ correspond to centroids in k-means
    • k-means centroids are independent between each other
    • Neurons in SOMs influence each other
    • SOMs can be seen as a constrained form of K-means
  • Difference between SOM and PCA
    • Iterative procedure organizes neurons location (through node’s weight) on a low-dimensional space
    • This forms a coordinate system to classify input data, which is similar to PCA

Self-Organizing Maps (SOM) with basic plots

What we do? (Code)

We create the following 4 SOM-plots:

  • Change-Plot: Shows the mean distance to the closest codebook vector during training
  • Count-Plot: Shows the number of objects mapped to the individual units. Empty units are depicted in gray
  • Mapping-Plot: Shows where objects are mapped
  • Dist.neighbours-Plot: Shows the sum of the distances to all immediate neighbours. Units near a class boundary can be expected to have higher average distances to their neighbours.
set.seed(88)

par(mfrow=c(2,2), cex.main = 0.6, cex.lab = 0.6, cex.axis = 0.6)

row_label <- as.factor(rownames(selection_data_only_numerical))
colors <- c("red", "black", "blue", "green")
colors <- colors[as.numeric(data_categorical_variable)]

data_train_matrix <- as.matrix(scale(data_unique2))

som_types <- c("changes", "count", "mapping", "dist.neighbours")
som_grid_dims <- c(4, 5, 6, 7)

for (j in som_grid_dims){
  som_grid <- somgrid(xdim = j,
                      ydim = j,
                      topo="hexagonal")
  som_model <- som(data_train_matrix,
                   grid=som_grid,
                   rlen=1000,
                   alpha=c(0.05,0.01),
                   keep.data = TRUE)
  for (i in som_types){
  plot(som_model,
       type=i,
       main=paste("Model fitted with parameters model (",i,") and xdim/ydim (",j,")"),
       col=colors[row_label])
  }
}

What we get? (Interpretation)

  • The loop-function generates 4 different plots for 4 different dimensions (4, 5, 6, 7). Generalization to N-dimensional data: This ordering of the neurons (~ ordering of centroids in K-means) forms a new coordinate system for the input features and is used to classify the inputs.
  • Change-Plot: The first plot visualizes the training process. As the SOM training iterations progress, the distance from each nodes weights to the samples represented by that node is reduced. Ideally, this distance should reach a minimum plateau. This plot option shows the progress over time. If the curve is continually decreasing, more iterations are required. Even dimension = 7 also reaches a minimum plateau, it needs the most iterations to get to it.
  • Count-Plot: The second plot visualizes the count of how many samples are mapped to each node on the map. This metric can be used as a measure of map quality - ideally the sample distribution is relatively uniform. Large values in some map areas suggests that a larger map would be beneficial. Empty nodes indicate that your map size is too big for the number of samples. Aim for at least 5-10 samples per node when choosing map size. We can see that the SOMs with Dim 6 and 7 have the biggest number of empty nodes (4).
  • Mapping-Plot: We can see that the objects are not distributed equally. The Plot with dim=5 has the better distribution compared to plot with dim=4. This is an indicator for a higher map quality.
  • "dist.neighbours-Plot: We can see where the sum of the distance to all neighbours are big or low. Units, which are near of a class boundary have a higher average distance to their neighbours.

Self-Organizing Maps (SOM) with heatmap

What we do? (Code)

Typical SOM visualizations are of heatmaps. A heatmap shows the distribution of a variable across the SOM. Therefore, we use the Property-Plot:

  • Property-Plot: Properties of each unit can be calculated and shown in color code. It can be used to visualize the similarity of one particular object to all units in the map.
set.seed(77)

par(cex = 0.9)

som_grid <- somgrid(xdim = 4,
                    ydim = 4,
                    topo="hexagonal")
som_model <- som(data_train_matrix,
                 grid=som_grid,
                 rlen=1000,
                 alpha=c(0.05,0.01),
                 keep.data = TRUE)

property_variables <- c(1,3,5,7,8)

for (i in property_variables){
  plot(som_model,
       type="property",
       property = getCodes(som_model, 1)[,i],
       main=paste("Property plot for variable",names(data_unique)[i]))
  }

What we get? (Interpretation)

  • Heatmaps are one of the most important visualization possibilities for Self-Organizing Maps. A SOM heatmap allows the visualisation of the distribution of a single variable across the map. Typically, a SOM investigative process involves the creation of multiple heatmaps, and then the comparison of these heatmaps to identify interesting areas on the map.
  • We can see that the nodes in the top right corner tend to have a positive value (+1.5) whereas the nodes in the bottom left corner have a negative value of around -1.

Self-Organizing Maps (SOM) with dendrogram

What we do? (Code)

In the next step, we try to cluster the observations. Therefore, we isolate groups of samples with similar metrics.

set.seed(92)

som_grid <- somgrid(xdim = 4,
                    ydim = 4,
                    topo="hexagonal")
som_model <- som(data_train_matrix,
                 grid=som_grid,
                 rlen=1000,
                 alpha=c(0.05,0.01),
                 keep.data = TRUE)

tree <- as.dendrogram(hclust(dist(as.numeric(unlist(som_model$codes)))))

plot(tree,
     main = "Tree with clustering som-grid",
     ylab = "Height (h)")

plot(tree,
     main = "Zoom into dendrogram",
     ylab = "Height (h)",
     xlim = c(1, 50),
     ylim = c(1,20),
     cex = 0.6)

What we get? (Interpretation)

  • The output above is a tree, which was created with SOM (clustering the observation with the defined som.grid)
  • The tree allows us to isolate groups of samples with similar metrics (e.g. player 6 and 32)

Self-Organizing Maps (SOM) with dendrogram and clustering

What we do? (Code)

In the next step, we cut the tree somewhere (e.g. h=4, based on tree above) and visualize mapping based on HC.

set.seed(77)

som_cluster <- cutree(hclust(dist(as.numeric(unlist(som_model$codes)))), h = 3)
pretty_palette <- c("#1f77b4", '#ff7f0e', '#2ca02c', '#d62728','#9467bd', '#8c564b', '#e377c2')

plot(som_model,
     type = "mapping",
     main = "Mapping som-plot",
     bgcol = pretty_palette[som_cluster],
     col = colors[row_label],
     cex.main = 0.8)
add.cluster.boundaries(som_model,som_cluster)

What we get? (Interpretation)

  • The Plot above show the Visualization of the mapping based on HC.
  • Ideally, the clusters found are contiguous on the map surface.
  • We can see that some of the clusters are connected. It is noticeable, that not all of the points in the clusters have the same color (representing the row label)
